description.plain:
Originally making songs in his basement for his friends as Sky Sailing, Adam Young then discovered synth music and became Owl City, releasing two relatively unpopular albums Maybe I’m Dreaming and Of June before making his hit single “Fireflies” which made his third album as Owl City, Ocean Eyes a hit.

After this worldwide success he put on two more albums, All Things Bright and Beautiful in 2011, and The Midsummer Station in 2012. In 2014 he released an EP, Ultraviolet, composed of 4 songs whom one would appear on his following album, Mobile Orchestra. Retiring from Owl City in 2016 to focus on Adam Young Scores, a new project made of orchestral soundtracks about historic events, he reappeared in 2017 to tease his upcoming new album Cinematic, with the release of a series of three EPs, called Reel 1 , 2 and 3.
Another album of his came out in 2023, under the name Coco Moon.

songs.title: Fireflies

description.plain:
“Fireflies”, Owl City’s debut single, was an international smash hit, effectively launching the genre Twee into the mainstream. It reached #1 in the US in November 2009.

The song was inspired by watching shooting stars during a camping trip with lyrics also influenced by insomnia. Adam Young said of “Fireflies” in an interview with Female First:

I have a bit of a problem falling asleep. Strangely enough it is when I can’t sleep that I tend to find most inspiration. I was up late and in the basement one night when I wrote ‘Fireflies’. I was sitting at the keyboard just fooling around, not really trying to write anything. Over the next couple of hours that song came together in the most natural way. I can’t explain it but it almost wrote itself. I didn’t have any idea that moment that I had written a hit.

The song also features uncredited vocals from the lead vocalist from Relient K, Matthew Thiessen.

songs.title: Vanilla Twilight

description.plain:
“Vanilla Twilight” is slower and softer than Owl City’s electronica songs, and radiates feelings of both coziness and melancholy at once. It tells of the narrator’s longing to be with a loved one who has, depending on your interpretation of the song, either moved or passed away.

It is the second single off of the 2009 album “Ocean Eyes,” and peaked at #72 on the Billboard Hot 100.

songs.title: Good Time

description.plain:
Carly Rae Jepsen of “Call Me Maybe” fame joins Owl City on this radio-friendly comeback single, which peaked at #8 on the Billboard Hot 100.

In October 2012, Jepsen and Adam Young (the man behind Owl City) were sued by Allyson Burnett, who claimed that they had copied her song, “Ah, It’s a Love Song”, which was released in 2010.

It was ruled that “Good Time” did not copy Burnett’s song.
